  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(5) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "All these were the sons of Heman.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Were sons to Heman.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The king’s seer in the words of God.—Or, in the things of God, in Divine (that is, liturgical) matters. Heman was a prophet as well as a minstrel. (For the connection between music and prophecy, comp. 1Samuel 10:5-6; 2Kings 3:15; Exodus 15:20.) Comp. also Note on 1Chronicles 25:1, above.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "The king’s seer in the words of God.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Or, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "in the things of God, in Divine",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " (that is, liturgical) ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "matters.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " Heman was a prophet as well as a minstrel. (For the connection between music and prophecy, comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Samuel 10:5-6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Kings 3:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Exodus 15:20",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".) Comp. also Note on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 25:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", above.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Seer.—Heb., hōzèh. Literally, gazer. The word rendered “seer” in 1Chronicles 26:28 and 1Samuel 9:9 is different (rō’èh). Gad was called “David’s seer” (1Chronicles 21:9); so also Jeduthun is “the king’s seer” (2Chronicles 35:15).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Seer.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Heb., ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "hōzèh.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " Literally, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "gazer.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " The word rendered “seer” in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 26:28",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Samuel 9:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " is different (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "rō’èh",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ")",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " Gad was called “David’s seer” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 21:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "); so also Jeduthun is “the king’s seer” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
